  "doc_id": "11338",
  "text": "Several previous studies discussed the nature of chemical species (nitric acid, sulfuric and methanesulfonic acid) involved in the dechlorination of sea-salt aerosol in Antarctica but no overall picture has emerged. Chloride can also be released from the reaction of gaseous HOBr with seasalt aerosol [CITATION_1] . The HOBr level at Concordia was investigated by [CITATION_2] , who reported mixing ratios close to 1 pptv in spring. For comparison, the HNO 3 level at Concordia reaches 0.5 nEq m −3 (i.e., ∼ 11 pptv) in October and more than 1 nEq m −3 in November-December (i.e., more than 22 pptv), suggesting that HOBr does not significantly contribute to the chloride depletion over the high Antarctic plateau in spring and summer. At coastal regions, in samplings made on denuder tubes at DDU, [CITATION_3] reported a bromide to nitrate mass ratio of 0.2 in summer and close to 1-2 in winter (a mean ratio of 0.7 being observed for September and October). That leads to a bromide to nitrate molar ratio of 0.5. Since, at that site, HOBr represents around a quarter of total inorganic bromine trapped together with nitric acid on denuders [CITATION_4] , we can conclude that, at least in East Antarctica, the contribution of HOBr in the chloride depletion of sea-salt aerosol cannot be totally ruled out, but it is certainly not a dominant process. Based on 12-stage impactor data, [CITATION_5] found that in January 1998 at the coastal site of Aboa, H 2 SO 4 particles account for slightly more of the observed dechlorination than HNO 3 whereas [CITATION_6] attributed most of the dechlorination to HNO 3 with little effect of the sulfur compounds at DDU (end of November to mid-December 2000). [CITATION_7] also showed that at coastal Halley station nitrate was reasonably wellcorrelated with sodium on the stages of an impactor associated with smaller sea-salt aerosol, suggesting an important role for nitrate in reacting with sea salt there.",
